As Kourt-jester wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/11/2004 at 14:08:08 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I have been stuggling with this for a while and i was hopeing you 
>could answer it for me.
>
>Dan is twice as old as Mike,
>Mike is 14 years younger than Ben,
>Ben is 4 years younger than Dan.
>How old is Ben?
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Let D, M and B be the ages of Dan, Mike and Ben, respectively.

Then:

D = 2M
M+14 = B
B = D-4

Can you solve it from here?  You just need a couple of
substitutions.


